<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>Saigon moment • sputnik moment</xh5><p> <i>Saigon moment</i>—(usually in military contexts) used when people realize that they will lose or fail <i>(originally of the U.S. negative experience in the Vietnam war):</i> “We are waiting for the final chapter, for your <u>Saigon moment</u>,” a rebel commander bragged in a taunt to U.S. President Bush.</p><p> <i>sputnik moment—</i>used when people realize that they are seriously challenged and have to redouble their efforts to catch up <i>(originally of the time when the Soviet Union launched the first satellite and beat the USA into space): </i>Hutchison warned that “we are on the verge of another <u>Sputnik moment</u>” because of China’s perceived lunar ambitions.</p> </entry>
